01:32:14.440 --> 01:32:18.250
going to present some new foundation models from his team that are not

1505
01:32:18.320 --> 01:32:21.910
just for pathology, but go beyond it and actually are

1506
01:32:21.940 --> 01:32:24.200
foundation models of everything.

1507
01:32:24.360 --> 01:32:27.920
So I would like to introduce Faisal here.

1508
01:32:28.000 --> 01:32:30.460
Please join me here on the stage, Faisal. Yep.

1509
01:32:35.720 --> 01:32:38.420
Thank you so much for the introduction and for inviting me to speak today.

1510
01:32:39.040 --> 01:32:42.040
So today I'll be talking about some of the work that my group has done in

1511
01:32:42.100 --> 01:32:44.800
developing foundation models for oncology.

1512
01:32:45.240 --> 01:32:48.900
We'll talk about some of the pathology foundation models that we have developed,

1513
01:32:49.520 --> 01:32:52.740
and also some of the new work that is coming out of our group.

1514
01:32:53.840 --> 01:32:54.900
Here are my disclosures.

1515
01:32:56.540 --> 01:33:00.340
So my group predominantly works on computational pathology, so we analyze images

1516
01:33:00.380 --> 01:33:04.270
that look something like this. So these are very large images

1517
01:33:04.300 --> 01:33:06.220
that come from digitized glass slides.

1518
01:33:07.500 --> 01:33:11.180
Pathology is often regarded as the last modality in cancer research to be

1519
01:33:11.220 --> 01:33:15.020
digitized, and that's because the standard of care still remains looking at a glass

1520
01:33:15.040 --> 01:33:18.880
slide under a microscope. And the goal of our team is really to go

1521
01:33:18.920 --> 01:33:22.280
from these images to everything in the red box here, from early diagnosis,

1522
01:33:22.380 --> 01:33:25.130
prognosis, looking at prediction of response to treatment, and so forth.

1523
01:33:25.880 --> 01:33:29.780
But we also integrate other kinds of data types to answer some of these

1524
01:33:29.820 --> 01:33:33.760
questions. So this is how we started to approach this problem of trying

1525
01:33:33.780 --> 01:33:34.600
to represent data

1526
01:33:35.820 --> 01:33:39.600
in a more meaningful way so we can do all of these different computational

1527
01:33:39.640 --> 01:33:40.440
tasks downstream.

1528
01:33:41.940 --> 01:33:44.460
So I always like to talk a little bit about the history of the field, and in

1529
01:33:44.480 --> 01:33:47.720
particular about Judith Prevette, because she was a forgotten hero

1530
01:33:47.840 --> 01:33:49.240
of this area.

1531
01:33:50.180 --> 01:33:53.500
She did some very interesting early work in the 1960s and '70s

1532
01:33:54.360 --> 01:33:56.640
in trying to analyze these microscopy images.

1533
01:33:57.980 --> 01:34:01.680
And what a lot of people don't know is that her work became the

1534
01:34:01.700 --> 01:34:04.000
basis of the very first FDA-approved

1535
01:34:04.940 --> 01:34:08.660
medical device that used some form of machine learning in the late

1536
01:34:08.760 --> 01:34:12.640
'80s and early '90s, and that was what's today is known as a

1537
01:34:12.720 --> 01:34:15.260
Genius Hologic device and is used for

1538
01:34:16.580 --> 01:34:20.440
Pap smear analysis and other kinds of cytology-based analysis.

1539
01:34:21.840 --> 01:34:25.750
But at the time, these images were very large, so they were

1540
01:34:25.760 --> 01:34:29.120
being patched and stored into magnetic tape and using simple line

1541
01:34:30.340 --> 01:34:34.060
profiles. So it's very interesting to see how her work has

1542
01:34:34.240 --> 01:34:37.960
had an influence on everything that is being done in computational

1543
01:34:37.980 --> 01:34:38.740
pathology today.

1544
01:34:39.620 --> 01:34:42.920
These images are very large, so in more recent times we've used all kinds of weakly

1545
01:34:42.960 --> 01:34:46.560
supervised methods. So these methods use whole slide images and

1546
01:34:46.880 --> 01:34:50.740
labels that reside in pathology reports or electronic medical records

1547
01:34:51.180 --> 01:34:54.800
to train these models. Two of the most common approaches for these

1548
01:34:54.940 --> 01:34:58.320
include the utility of graph convolutional neural networks or

1549
01:34:58.760 --> 01:35:01.860
multiple instance learning. So in

1550
01:35:02.420 --> 01:35:03.040
2019,

1551
01:35:04.280 --> 01:35:07.560
this real seminal article was published from the Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer

1552
01:35:07.620 --> 01:35:11.300
Center, where they showed that you needed about 10,000 or so whole slide images to

1553
01:35:11.360 --> 01:35:14.400
train a model that would get you to useful clinical

1554
01:35:14.480 --> 01:35:15.520
performance.

1555
01:35:16.420 --> 01:35:19.520
And when we started working in the area, we wanted to see if there's a

1556
01:35:19.540 --> 01:35:21.520
data-efficient way for us to do this.

1557
01:35:22.140 --> 01:35:25.760
And that's what led to a number of studies, but we came up with methods and

1558
01:35:25.800 --> 01:35:29.740
tools that we used to train machine learning models using

1559
01:35:29.780 --> 01:35:31.880
whole slide images and labels

1560
01:35:32.780 --> 01:35:35.980
that did not need pixel-level annotations.

1561
01:35:35.990 --> 01:35:36.260
And

1562
01:35:37.160 --> 01:35:40.140
we were able to do this in a data-efficient manner, which means we could apply it

1563
01:35:40.160 --> 01:35:41.620
to much more interesting problems.

1564
01:35:42.440 --> 01:35:45.620
We also made these tools publicly available, so there's an entire community of

1565
01:35:45.660 --> 01:35:48.540
people that have used these tools over the past six or seven years.

1566
01:35:49.100 --> 01:35:53.050
We applied this to cancer of unknown primary in 2021, trying to see if

1567
01:35:53.100 --> 01:35:56.900
we can predict origins for metastatic and unknown primary tumors

1568
01:35:57.240 --> 01:36:01.040
using a histology image alone. We looked at endomyocardial

1569
01:36:01.080 --> 01:36:05.050
biopsy assessment and also trying to integrate histology and molecular

1570
01:36:05.140 --> 01:36:08.580
data to see if we'll be able to build better

1571
01:36:08.600 --> 01:36:09.620
prognostic models.

1572
01:36:10.940 --> 01:36:14.240
But for all of these tools, we used multiple instance learning-based

1573
01:36:14.500 --> 01:36:18.060
framework, which uses whole slide image, which is patched into smaller

1574
01:36:18.140 --> 01:36:21.960
patches. We extract meaningful representations from these patches and

1575
01:36:22.000 --> 01:36:24.500
then learn on top of those representations.

1576
01:36:24.620 --> 01:36:28.260
Our earlier studies, the studies I just showed, used representations

1577
01:36:28.620 --> 01:36:32.200
that were just based on a ResNet that's trained on real-world images.

1578
01:36:33.840 --> 01:36:37.320
But they still performed reasonably, but over time, we realized that the feature

1579
01:36:37.340 --> 01:36:40.840
extraction component here is very important, and how we represent

1580
01:36:40.920 --> 01:36:44.480
these data is key to

1581
01:36:44.540 --> 01:36:47.060
improving these predictive models.

1582
01:36:47.390 --> 01:36:50.960
So we started experimenting with self-supervised learning early on, and then in

1583
01:36:51.040 --> 01:36:53.580
2024, we published these two foundation models.

1584
01:36:53.590 --> 01:36:57.580
And these foundation models focus on extracting meaningful representations from

1585
01:36:57.600 --> 01:36:58.470
pathology images,

1586
01:36:59.320 --> 01:37:02.380
but also trying to contrast with text to improve image

1587
01:37:03.020 --> 01:37:06.250
representations. This is just in line with what has happened in the machine

1588
01:37:06.280 --> 01:37:09.340
learning community, where they've tried to contrast images with text

1589
01:37:09.380 --> 01:37:13.240
representation to improve image representation.

1590
01:37:13.280 --> 01:37:16.760
So these models were made publicly available and have been downloaded over four

1591
01:37:16.820 --> 01:37:20.600
million times and have been used at this point in over 2,000 different studies.

1592
01:37:21.520 --> 01:37:25.060
So this really accelerated the utility of these models show that how

1593
01:37:25.420 --> 01:37:29.200
important self-supervision is and how important representing data into meaningful

1594
01:37:29.240 --> 01:37:33.080
representations can be. So these studies were focusing on

1595
01:37:33.100 --> 01:37:36.776
representing... regions of pathology slides, but we also wanted to

1596
01:37:36.816 --> 01:37:40.716
scale this to the entire slide. So last year we published Titan,

1597
01:37:40.776 --> 01:37:44.636
which is a foundation model that focuses on representing the entirety of a whole

1598
01:37:44.696 --> 01:37:47.656
slide image into a singular vector or representation.

1599
01:37:49.176 --> 01:37:52.896
And this used a number of different bells and whistles, including iBOT-based

1600
01:37:53.516 --> 01:37:55.946
training and using what's commonly used for

1601
01:37:56.976 --> 01:38:00.476
training large language models, where we train short and test long,

1602
01:38:00.736 --> 01:38:04.636
and train on a limited region of the slide and testing on a large region of

1603
01:38:04.716 --> 01:38:08.376
the slide. But we also used additional layers of

1604
01:38:08.456 --> 01:38:12.176
training, which includes using text, both from the

1605
01:38:12.216 --> 01:38:15.846
report and a generative model that had been developed in our group.

1606
01:38:15.876 --> 01:38:19.486
And we tried to show that we can improve slide level representations in

1607
01:38:19.516 --> 01:38:22.196
contrast with some of the other foundation models that were out there.

1608
01:38:22.256 --> 01:38:25.136
Also, we assessed what the scaling laws looked like.

1609
01:38:25.236 --> 01:38:29.096
And as our models are getting better, our benchmarks are also getting more

1610
01:38:29.116 --> 01:38:32.676
complex and difficult because all of the problems that we were trying to target

1611
01:38:33.036 --> 01:38:34.196
back in 2024,

1612
01:38:35.016 --> 01:38:38.566
these models already perform almost perfectly on those

1613
01:38:39.356 --> 01:38:39.716
tasks.

1614
01:38:40.716 --> 01:38:44.156
So we tried to represent the whole slide,

1615
01:38:44.836 --> 01:38:47.256
and we made these models publicly available as well.

1616
01:38:48.476 --> 01:38:52.216
But text is a very subjective modality, so we also

1617
01:38:52.836 --> 01:38:55.656
wanted to explore that can we contrast

1618
01:38:56.596 --> 01:39:00.006
with additional modalities such that it will improve image representation?

1619
01:39:00.056 --> 01:39:02.776
And there's a lot of more objective information about these

1620
01:39:03.616 --> 01:39:05.316
cases that we have available to us.

1621
01:39:05.346 --> 01:39:07.456
So we started contrasting with molecular information.

1622
01:39:07.496 --> 01:39:10.856
We started by looking at IHCs, contrasting with IHCs to see if the

1623
01:39:10.876 --> 01:39:14.616
representation would improve, and then doing the same

1624
01:39:14.796 --> 01:39:18.476
with molecular data or transcriptomics in a really toy-based setting.

1625
01:39:18.516 --> 01:39:21.696
So this is just by using the TCGA. And we showed that you could really improve

1626
01:39:21.796 --> 01:39:23.336
few-shot performance

1627
01:39:24.276 --> 01:39:27.856
quite a lot. That means using very, very few labels or very, very few

1628
01:39:27.936 --> 01:39:28.866
samples for training

1629
01:39:30.096 --> 01:39:30.666
these models,

1630
01:39:31.876 --> 01:39:35.356
and still converging to a clinically useful result.

1631
01:39:35.376 --> 01:39:38.526
So this was early indication that this is an approach that we should scale, and

1632
01:39:38.556 --> 01:39:42.485
that's where we started to develop Threads, which is a model that uses

1633
01:39:42.556 --> 01:39:46.506
all of the molecular data that was available to us at MGB as well as at

1634
01:39:46.516 --> 01:39:50.336
Dana-Farber, where we tried to contrast between H&amp;E

1635
01:39:50.496 --> 01:39:52.356
images and corresponding molecular

1636
01:39:53.196 --> 01:39:56.896
data. To improve representation, we showed that you could focus on or

1637
01:39:56.976 --> 01:40:00.416
target more difficult problems like treatment response prediction

1638
01:40:00.796 --> 01:40:02.256
directly from the histology slide.

1639
01:40:03.296 --> 01:40:06.916
So this is a study that will come out in the coming months, and we do have plans to

1640
01:40:06.936 --> 01:40:09.076
make this model publicly available as well.

1641
01:40:10.256 --> 01:40:14.236
We also try to expand this to spatial proteomic

1642
01:40:14.416 --> 01:40:18.236
data. So this is a model for spatial proteomics that we developed

1643
01:40:18.256 --> 01:40:21.136
in the group using large amounts of data and self-supervision.

1644
01:40:21.436 --> 01:40:24.786
The goal is the same. Can we represent proteomic data into meaningful

1645
01:40:24.816 --> 01:40:28.296
representations that can then be used for a host of different downstream tasks?

1646
01:40:28.636 --> 01:40:32.586
This includes tissue phenotyping, looking at artifact classification and so forth,

1647
01:40:32.656 --> 01:40:36.276
but also using it as a search engine to retrieve

1648
01:40:36.676 --> 01:40:40.516
similar regions within spatial proteomic data, as well as for spatial

1649
01:40:40.536 --> 01:40:43.976
biomarker discovery. So we have an earlier version of this model that was already

1650
01:40:44.036 --> 01:40:48.016
made available, and if people would like to get access to the newer

1651
01:40:48.036 --> 01:40:50.396
version of the model, there's a QR code that you can use

1652
01:40:50.476 --> 01:40:54.376
to sign up for the new version that will

1653
01:40:54.396 --> 01:40:56.316
be coming out. And my colleague, Shizun,

1654
01:40:57.316 --> 01:41:00.436
will be giving a talk about this, and we also have a poster on this

1655
01:41:01.096 --> 01:41:04.226
foundation model, and hopefully the study will also come out later this year.

1656
01:41:05.676 --> 01:41:09.396
But as we have continued to develop these models, we started

1657
01:41:09.436 --> 01:41:13.036
by looking at regions within a pathology slide, which we tried to

1658
01:41:13.076 --> 01:41:15.976
contrast with other modalities to improve image representation.

1659
01:41:16.016 --> 01:41:19.816
We scaled it to the entirety of the slide, and then we can represent the

1660
01:41:19.856 --> 01:41:23.596
whole slide. But something that we've been trying to do

1661
01:41:23.676 --> 01:41:27.536
for the past three years or so is trying to represent the entire

1662
01:41:27.576 --> 01:41:31.306
patient. So now it's commonly referred to as virtual patient representation,

1663
01:41:31.396 --> 01:41:35.216
but at the time, we just called it representing the entire patient's

1664
01:41:35.316 --> 01:41:35.636
record.

1665
01:41:37.236 --> 01:41:41.096
The goal was that can we use everything digital that we

1666
01:41:41.236 --> 01:41:45.116
have about the patient and represent the patient into a singular

1667
01:41:45.196 --> 01:41:48.616
vector that can then be used for a lot of different downstream

1668
01:41:49.676 --> 01:41:53.216
applications? And these applications can be

1669
01:41:53.496 --> 01:41:56.956
predictive. They can be related to diagnosis, prognosis, treatment response

1670
01:41:56.976 --> 01:42:00.496
prediction, next event prediction, hospital operations.

1671
01:42:01.176 --> 01:42:04.356
But just having something that represents the patient

1672
01:42:05.296 --> 01:42:08.176
into a meaningful representation would be incredibly valuable.

1673
01:42:08.236 --> 01:42:11.826
And we wanted this to be dynamic and continuously updating because we have a lot of

1674
01:42:11.856 --> 01:42:13.796
information about the patient

1675
01:42:14.756 --> 01:42:18.676
at any given point in time, but that information also continues

1676
01:42:18.736 --> 01:42:22.636
to evolve as we get more and more data into

1677
01:42:22.656 --> 01:42:25.976
the system. So we used all of the data that was available to us at

1678
01:42:26.496 --> 01:42:30.086
Mass General Brigham. This includes about 12 hospitals,

1679
01:42:30.956 --> 01:42:34.756
and this is data from about 7.2 million patients that were used to

1680
01:42:34.776 --> 01:42:38.566
develop this model, and it has about 18 different modalities.

1681
01:42:38.596 --> 01:42:42.096
And the goal is that as more and more data will become available about the patient,

1682
01:42:42.156 --> 01:42:45.856
we will represent it into a singular vector or singular representation for that

1683
01:42:45.876 --> 01:42:48.956
patient. So the representation would evolve

1684
01:42:49.376 --> 01:42:53.096
over time, and we'll also have a patient trajectory as to how the

1685
01:42:53.136 --> 01:42:55.176
patient and its representation evolves.

1686
01:42:57.176 --> 01:43:01.076
So once we have this representation, we can look at risks, predictions,

1687
01:43:01.096 --> 01:43:04.116
similarity searching, statistical analysis, other kinds of treatment response

1688
01:43:04.416 --> 01:43:07.796
predictions. So the single vector would be incredibly useful for us, right?

1689
01:43:07.876 --> 01:43:11.686
So these are all downstream tasks or applications that we can potentially

1690
01:43:12.196 --> 01:43:15.196
look at. But once we have these representations,

1691
01:43:16.276 --> 01:43:20.016
we can look at how the different concepts in

1692
01:43:20.056 --> 01:43:23.815
medicine cluster together. This is a very nice plot

1693
01:43:23.896 --> 01:43:27.676
where we have an entire atlas of medicine being learned on

1694
01:43:27.716 --> 01:43:29.256
its own from these

1695
01:43:30.116 --> 01:43:32.856
representations. And you can look at the fact that

1696
01:43:32.896 --> 01:43:36.240
particularontologies

1697
01:43:36.660 --> 01:43:40.560
that we know from literature all clustered

1698
01:43:40.600 --> 01:43:42.940
together, even though they were not given to the model

1699
01:43:43.940 --> 01:43:47.800
during training. The model is unaware of all the literature

1700
01:43:47.810 --> 01:43:51.540
that we have about these different ontologies, and yet it

1701
01:43:51.580 --> 01:43:54.920
manages to cluster these ontologies all together.

1702
01:43:57.100 --> 01:44:00.580
And then you can also go in and study different relationships that

1703
01:44:00.600 --> 01:44:02.980
exist across modalities.

1704
01:44:03.860 --> 01:44:07.680
These are all ways to see how rich these representations are and

1705
01:44:07.720 --> 01:44:10.469
how meaningful representations does the model

1706
01:44:11.420 --> 01:44:11.720
learn?

1707
01:44:13.160 --> 01:44:15.740
We can also look at individual embeddings.

1708
01:44:15.760 --> 01:44:17.500
So in this case, each dot represents the

1709
01:44:19.260 --> 01:44:23.000
embedding of the entire patient, or everything that we know about the patient,

1710
01:44:23.060 --> 01:44:26.540
including structured and unstructured data, and it's colored by

1711
01:44:27.160 --> 01:44:27.560
age.

1712
01:44:29.060 --> 01:44:32.320
And then once you have these embeddings and these

1713
01:44:32.360 --> 01:44:36.219
representations, you're also able to look for similar

1714
01:44:36.260 --> 01:44:39.920
patients. So in an entire record, in a large record, are you able

1715
01:44:40.219 --> 01:44:44.100
to find similar patients? Because similarity search or patient

1716
01:44:44.160 --> 01:44:48.060
matching is a problem that can solve a lot of issues that we

1717
01:44:48.100 --> 01:44:51.020
have, both in oncology and in medicine in general.

